<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-682-188  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 682 188.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  Sept 18 1989 v15 n19 p32(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ATandamp;T's big push to stay ahead of environmental woes. (includesrelated article on unions' attitudes toward AT and T)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Berkman, Barbara N.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>AT and T is leading its industry in attempts to be environmentallyresponsible.andP;  The telecommunications giant is attempting toeliminate all chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) from its manufacturingprocess by 1994.andP;  AT and T uses one-third of the electronicindustry's CFCs, and is the fifth largest emitter of thechemicals.andP;  IBM set a similar internal goal to rid itself of CFCsby 1993, but AT and T announced its goal publicly.andP;  According toenvironmentalists and the US Environmental Protection Agency, ATand T has set the industry standard for corporate environmentalpolicies regarding CFCs, hazardous waste and worker safety.andP;  DavidChittick is AT and T's VP in charge of the environment and safetyengineering.andP;  He is responsible for worldwide enforcement of thecompany's environmental policy.andP;  He is also the liaison betweenthe company, the media and environmental groups.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (environmental policy).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     ChlorofluorocarbonsTelecommunicationsEnvironmental ProtectionManufacturing.andO;Feature:   illustrationtableportrait.andO;Caption:   ATandamp;T's corporate environmental policy. (table)David Chittick. (portrait)Person:    Chittick, David (environmental policy).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>